NARRATIVE:

On June 17th,20222, at approximately 1200 hours, I, Tfc. Elmore was operating patrol vehicle, I-54 in Queen Anne County, Maryland. On that date and time, I responded to Royal Farms 32303 Queen Anne Highway, Queen Anne, MD for the report of a Hit and Run. Upon arriving, I was directed by the complainant, Jermaine Bryant, to the suspect vehicle, a Volkswagon Jetta bearing Maryland registration "61471CF" which was stationary in the parking lot. Bryant advised the Jetta ran into the back of his Nissan Van on MD 309 at the westbound MD 404 intersection, then left the accident scene by continuing on westbound MD 404. Bryant advised the Jetta made a U-turn onto eastbound MD 404 and turned in the Royal Farm parking lot. Bryant advised when he pulled behind the Jetta, the driver attempted to leave again, but was blocked in by Bryant's vehicle.
Upon approaching the Jetta, I observed the driver to be accompanied by a dog and instructed him to exit the vehicle, he complied. I identified the driver as Andrew Scott Miller. I smelled a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from Miller's breath and person, his speech was slurred, and he was swaying left to right. During the investigation, I had to hold Miller by the back of shirt to help him maintain his balance. Miller struggled to answer routine questions such as "where do you live?". Miller also admitted to having an alcoholic beverage earlier in the day around 9am-10am. During my contact with Miller, he lost his balance and fell on the ground. I had to physically help him get up off the ground and help him sit down on curb of parking lot. Emergency Medical Services responded to the scene to check out Bryant and Miller. Bryant was transported to the University of Maryland Shore Medical Center at Easton for his complainant of back pain. Miller refused to be treated. I then offered Miller the Standardized Field Sobriety Test. During the test, Miller displayed the following clues: Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus:6 of 6, Walk and Turn: 8 of 8, One Leg Stand: 2of 4, and refused the Preliminary Breath Test. Based on my Training, knowledge, and experience, including prior DUI investigation, I determined Miller was driving under the influence of alcohol and placed him under arrest. Miller was read and allowed to read his rights via Dr-15, and he consented to a breath alcohol concentration test which he provided a breath specimen which was found to contain an alcohol concentration of .25 grams of alcohol per 210 liters of breath. Sergeant Howard, Cambridge Police Department, administered the test at Cambridge Police Department. It is to be noted CPD was approximately a 40-minute drive from the location of arrest. Miller was subsequently issued related traffic citations and released to the care of his mother. All events occurred in Maryland. 



VEHICLE IN MOTION: NOT OBSERVED


PERSONAL CONTACT: 
Miller was the driver and sole occupant in the vehicle
Miller admitted to consuming alcoholic beverages prior to driving 
 I smelled a Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from Miller's breath and person
 I observed Miller's eyes glassy and speech slurred 
Miller fell down on the ground after losing his balance 

PRE-ARREST SCREENING:

    I administered the SFST on the paved roadway. The roadway portion was clear of debris and closed from traffic flow 

 

HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS TEST: 6 OF 6 

    During the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus Test, I instructed Miller to follow  my pen as the stimulus with his eyes without moving his head. Miller stated he could see the tip of the pen and understood my instructions. Millers eyes were blue during the test

 

Miller displayed a lack of smooth pursuit in both eyes.

Miller displayed distinct and sustained Nystagmus at maximum deviation in both eyes.

Miller displayed an Onset of Nystagmus prior to 45 degrees in both eyes.

 

WALK AND TURN TEST: 8 OF 8  

    During the Walk and Turn Test, I instructed Miller to stand with both hands to his sides and place his right foot heel to toe in front of his left foot. I instructed Miller to remain in the position while I finish the instructions and demonstrate the test. I then instructed him to take nine heel-to-toe steps on a straight line, turn around by taking small steps while keeping the lead foot planted and pivoting, and take nine heel-to-toe steps back. I instructed Miller to keep his eyes on his feet, count his steps out loud, and keep his hands to his sides. I then demonstrated the test. Miller advised he understood the instructions.

 

    Miller could not maintain his balance during the instructional phase, He separated his feet.Miller attempted to start the test before instructed while I was still providing him with the instructions After the instructional phase, Miller started the walk and turn test. During the first nine steps, Miller missed heel to toe(steps1-9), stepped offline(steps1-9) raised his arms to balance, stepped approximately 23 times, and stopped due to forgetting the instructions. Unsatisfactory Turn. I had to remind Miller to turn around and continue the second nine steps. During the second nine steps, Miller missed heel to toe(steps 1-9), stepped offline(steps 1-9), and raised his arms for balance. Miller kept his arms approximately 45 degrees off of his body to maintain his balance.

 

ONE LEG STAND TEST: 2 of 4
    During the One Leg Stand Test, I instructed Miller to stand with both hands to his sides, choose either leg to lift approximately six inches off the ground, and count one thousand one, one thousand two, one thousand three, and so forth until I told him to stop. 

 

  I timed Miller for 30 seconds. Miller balanced by standing with his right foot on the ground. 

 
Within the 30 seconds, Miller swayed side to side and put his foot down approximately 4-5 times to maintain his balance

 

PRELIMINARY BREATH TEST: REFUSED

ADDITIONAL TEST:
PUPILLARY LIGHT RESPONSE TEST: NO PUPILLARY ABNORMALITIES WERE FOUND
